There are time when you need not just to display but also take inputs and what good are they good for if you cant use them in the code.
And for the here are 2 ways on how to do it one is by using the "ViewChild" in the Ts script and the other would be the " [(ngModel)]" in the html file.

The ngModel is not part of your starting project by default so you have to import it in the app.module.ts file first together with the FormsModule in order for you can use it.

<div class="code-obj"><pre class="prettyprint linenums codeContainer"> 
//app.module.ts
import { BrowserModule } from '@angular/platform-browser';
import { NgModule } from '@angular/core';
import { FormsModule } from '@angular/forms';

import { AppRoutingModule } from './app-routing.module';
import { AppComponent } from './app.component';
import { HowToInputFieldComponent } from './com/how-to-input-field/how-to-input-field.component';

@NgModule({
  declarations: [
    AppComponent,
    HowToInputFieldComponent,
  ],
  imports: [BrowserModule, AppRoutingModule, FormsModule],
  providers: [],
  bootstrap: [AppComponent],
})
export class AppModule {}

</pre></div>
<div class="code-obj"><pre class="prettyprint linenums codeContainer"> 
//Ts File
import { Component, OnInit, ViewChild, ElementRef } from '@angular/core';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-how-to-input-field',
  templateUrl: './how-to-input-field.component.html',
  styleUrls: ['./how-to-input-field.component.css'],
})
export class HowToInputFieldComponent implements OnInit {
  @ViewChild('secondInput') secondInput: ElementRef;

  theFirst: string = '';
  theSecond: string = '';

  constructor() {}

  ngOnInit(): void {}
  //Get the value from the viewchild and asignt it to theSecond
  updateSecond(): void {
    this.theSecond = this.secondInput.nativeElement.value;
  }
}
</pre></div>
<div class="code-obj"><pre class="prettyprint linenums codeContainer"> 
//HTML File
&ltdiv&gt
  &lt!-- First method using ngModel --&gt
  &ltlabel for="first"&gtThis would be the ngModel&lt/label&gt
  &ltbr /&gt
  &ltinput
    type="text"
    name="first"
    [(ngModel)]="theFirst"
    placeholder="First..."
  /&gt
  &ltp&gtvalue 1: {{ theFirst }}&lt/p&gt
  &ltp [innerText]="theFirst"&gt&lt/p&gt
  &lt!-- Second method using ViewChild --&gt
  &ltlabel for="second"&gt This would be the ViewChild&lt/label&gt
  &ltbr /&gt
  &ltinput type="text" 
  #secondInput 
  name="second" 
  placeholder="Second..." 
  /&gt
  &ltbr /&gt
  &ltbutton (click)="updateSecond()"&gtCheck Input Value&lt/button&gt
  &ltp&gtvalue 2: {{ theSecond }}&lt/p&gt
  &ltp [innerText]="theSecond"&gt&lt/p&gt
&lt/div&gt

</pre></div>
This is how this code would look like:
<img class="imgObj" src="https://i.imgur.com/SBx0gvS.png"/>
With the ngModule the variable is updated every time the input value is changed.
<img class="imgObj" src="https://i.imgur.com/mF4Tt9r.png"/>
But with the ViewChild it's just keeping track to the input reference and thus the variable is not updated.
<img class="imgObj" src="https://i.imgur.com/9DvgZjj.png"/>
You could add (onChange) in the html input field but for this example i just added a button for that.
(after pressiong the button the variable is updated)
